<HEADLINE>
<P>
PIERCE FARM'S FUTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ruth Loring's thoughtful, imaginative letter on the Pierce College Farm (Nov. 
12) echoes my sentiments perfectly. I will go a giant step further than her 
suggestions and ask why not use the land for a Valley arboretum? 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles County has arboretums in the San Gabriel Valley and South Coast. 
Doesn't the Valley need an arboretum more than additional religious sites or 
high-rises? 
</P>
<P>
Having lived 61 of my 62 years in Westlake Village, this summer I discovered 
Pierce College Farm. 
</P>
<P>
With hardly any student traffic afoot or in cars, it was easy to explore the 
back country of the campus: the country store, the acres of orchards, the 
cornfields, the rangeland, the nature trail and horticulture buildings. 
</P>
<P>
What I found appalled me. In this natural setting of potential great beauty and 
tranquillity, I found gross neglect and shabbiness. 
</P>
<P>
Hopefully this open space will be preserved for the community college to 
develop (or other governmental agencies if necessary) to its highest potential 
as a place for all the people to use. 
</P>
<P>
JENNY ERICKSON 
</P>
<P>
Westlake Village 
</P>
