<TEXT>
<P>
Former Tennessee gubernatorial candidate Jake Butcher pleaded guilty in federal 
court today to charges that he defrauded a Florida bank. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge G. Kendall Sharp accepted the plea, part of a plea bargain 
with the prosecution, and scheduled a sentencing hearing for March 21, an 
official in his office said. 
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the plea bargain, the former banker admitted to two counts 
of defrauding the Florida Center Bank of Orlando and conspiracy charges against 
him were dropped, said Edward Garland, Butcher's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
Butcher admitted using proceeds from a bank loan for purposes other than those 
stipulated by the loan agreement, Garland said. He was indicted on 19 counts of 
fraud by an Orlando grand jury Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
The indictment charged that Butcher and several others defrauded the bank of 
about $3 million. 
