<TEXT>
<P>
Michigan free safety Vada Murray, who was briefly knocked out in the 
Wolverines' 28-18 victory over Ohio State, said he'll take it easy before 
preparing for the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
Murray was knocked out in the final minutes of Saturday's game in Ann Arbor. He 
was released Sunday from University of Michigan Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
"I was only out for a minute," the senior from Cincinnati said. "But it was a 
minute too long for me. You play a sport all your life, and in a second it can 
be gone." 
</P>
<P>
Murray said he planned to take a few days off from practice before Rose Bowl 
conditioning begins this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
The No. 3 Wolverines (10-1) will face 12th-ranked Southern California (8-2-1) 
on New Year's Day in Pasadena. 
